Study 4

Analyses

28 January, 2022

Notes

Both MHS and MASS have been scored for this study so that higher scores are desirable, i.e., represent lower homophobia. This is so that (a) there is a congruent interpretation of directionality in the analyses, and (b) so that positive Cohens d scores in the meta analyses represent improvement, which is typical.

Error bars are 95% Confidence Intervals calculated as 1.96 +/- SE, where Standard Errors are calculated from the data directly (i.e., the empirical SEs by condition, not the model-implied SEs in the case of repeated-measures plots), where SE = SD/sqrt(N). Inferences are not made on the basis of these plots (e.g., based on the CIs) but on the basis of the ANOVAs and any required contrast tests (with familywise corrections). In addition to this, there are not models fitted to the raw data, only the between time-point difference scores. As such, there are no model-implied SEs to calculate CIs from.

# make directory
dir.create("plots")

# plotting function
plot_descriptives <- function(data_raw, data_summary){
  ggplot(data = data_summary) +
    geom_point(data = data_raw, 
               aes(x = timepoint, 
                   y = score, 
                   shape = condition_level,
                   color = condition_level,
                   group = condition_level),
               position = position_jitterdodge(dodge.width = 0.3,
                                               jitter.width = 0.1),
               size = 1,
               alpha = 0.35) +
    geom_line(data = data_summary, 
              aes(x = timepoint, 
                  y = mean, 
                  color = condition_level,
                  group = condition_level),
              position = position_dodge(width = 0.3)) +
    geom_errorbar(data = data_summary, 
                  aes(x = timepoint, 
                      y = mean, 
                      ymin = mean - se*1.96, 
                      ymax = mean + se*1.96,
                      color = condition_level,
                      group = condition_level),
                  width = 0.2,
                  position = position_dodge(width = 0.3)) + 
    geom_point(data = data_summary, 
               aes(x = timepoint, 
                   y = mean, 
                   shape = condition_level,
                   color = condition_level,
                   group = condition_level),
               position = position_dodge(width = 0.3), 
               size = 2) +
    theme_linedraw() + 
    scale_color_viridis_d(begin = 0.3, end = 0.7, 
                          name = "Level of participant burden",
                          labels = c("Read", "Read + PT", "Read + rewrite")) +
    scale_shape_manual(name = "Level of participant burden",
                       labels = c("Read", "Read + PT", "Read + rewrite"),
                       values = c(16, 15, 17)) +
    xlab("Timepoint") +
    facet_wrap(~ condition_type_of_pt, ncol = 1, nrow = 2)
}


plot_two_way_interaction <- function(data) {
  ggplot(data,
         aes(x = condition_type_of_pt, 
             y = mean, 
             shape = condition_level,
             color = condition_level,
             group = condition_level)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
    #geom_line(position = position_dodge(width = 0.3)) +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean - se*1.96, ymax = mean + se*1.96),
                  width = 0.2,
                  position = position_dodge(width = 0.3)) + 
    geom_point(position = position_dodge(width = 0.3), 
               size = 2) +
    theme_linedraw() + 
    scale_color_viridis_d(begin = 0.3, end = 0.7, name = "Level of participant burden") +
    scale_shape_manual(name = "Level of participant burden",
                       labels = c("Read", "Read + PT", "Read + rewrite"),
                       values = c(16, 15, 17)) +
    xlab("Intervention type")
}

Get data

  • NB MASS, MHS-G and MHS-L are all scored so that higher scores represent less homophobia, i.e., so that an increase in scores from pre to post/followup represents improvement.
data_processed <- read_csv("../data/processed/data_processed.csv")

data_processed_after_exclusions <- data_processed %>%
  filter(exclude == FALSE) %>%
  mutate(id = as.factor(id),
         condition_type_of_pt = case_when(condition_type_of_pt == "modelled" ~ "Modelled",
                                          condition_type_of_pt == "traditional" ~ "Traditional"),
         condition_type_of_pt = fct_relevel(as.factor(condition_type_of_pt), "Traditional", "Modelled"),
         condition_level = case_when(condition_level == "read" ~ "Read",
                                     condition_level == "read_plus_rewrite_from_1st_person" ~ "Read_rewrite",
                                     condition_level == "read_plus_instruction_to_PT" ~ "Read_PT"),
         condition_level = as.factor(condition_level),
         attrition_at_followup = fct_relevel(as.factor(attrition_at_followup), "TRUE", "FALSE"))

# the way that ezANOVA parses cells throws an erroneous error when cells contain the character "+", so recode just for plotting
data_for_plotting <- data_processed_after_exclusions %>%
  mutate(condition_level = case_when(as.character(condition_level) == "Read" ~ "Read",
                                     as.character(condition_level) == "Read_rewrite" ~ "Read + rewrite",
                                     as.character(condition_level) == "Read_PT" ~ "Read + PT"),
         condition_level = as.factor(condition_level))

Descriptive plots

MASS

data_temp_mass <- data_processed_after_exclusions %>% 
  select(Pre = mass_pre_sum_score, 
         Post = mass_post_sum_score, 
         Followup = mass_followup_sum_score, 
         condition_type_of_pt, condition_level) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  pivot_longer(names_to = "timepoint",
               values_to = "score",
               cols = c("Pre", "Post", "Followup")) %>%
  mutate(timepoint = fct_relevel(timepoint, "Pre", "Post", "Followup"))

data_temp_summary_mass <- data_temp_mass %>%
  group_by(condition_type_of_pt, condition_level, timepoint) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(score),
            se = plotrix::std.error(score),
            sd = sd(score))

data_temp_summary_mass %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, round, digits = 2) %>%
  select(-se) %>%
  rename(`Type of PT` = condition_type_of_pt,
         `Level` = condition_level,
         Timepoint = timepoint,
         M = mean,
         SD = sd) %>%
  kable() %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"), full_width = FALSE)

ANOVAs and plots

  • Error bars are 95% CIs.
  • Type III sum of squares

Pre-post

MASS

# fit anova
fit_mass_post <- 
  ezANOVA(data     = data_processed_after_exclusions,
          dv       = mass_diff_pre_post,
          between  = .(condition_type_of_pt, condition_level),
          wid      = id,
          type     = 3,
          detailed = TRUE)

# automatically format results
anova_out(fit_mass_post, print = FALSE)$`--- FORMATTED RESULTS ------------------------------------` %>%
  # print
  kable() %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"), full_width = FALSE)
Effect Text
(Intercept) F(1, 162) = 4.43, p = .037, np2 = .03
condition_type_of_pt F(1, 162) = 0.83, p = .364, np2 = .01
condition_level F(2, 162) = 0.28, p = .759, np2 < .01
condition_type_of_pt:condition_level F(2, 162) = 0.41, p = .667, np2 < .01 
# plot
plot_prepost_mass <- data_for_plotting %>% 
  select(mass_diff_pre_post, condition_type_of_pt, condition_level) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  group_by(condition_type_of_pt, condition_level) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(mass_diff_pre_post),
            se = plotrix::std.error(mass_diff_pre_post)) %>%
  plot_two_way_interaction() +
  ylab("Difference between\npre and post")

Shaprio-Wilks tests

tidy_shaprio_wilks_test <- function(data) {
  fit <- shapiro.test(data$score)
  
  results <- tibble(W = round(fit$statistic, 2),
                    p = fit$p.value)
  
  return(results)
}

full_join(
  data_reshaped %>%
    group_by(scale, condition) %>%
    do(tidy_shaprio_wilks_test(.)),
  data_reshaped %>%
    count(scale, condition),
  by = c("scale", "condition")
) %>%
  mutate(p = round(p, 3)) %>%
  select(scale, condition, n, W, p) %>%
  kable()  %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"), full_width = FALSE)

ANOVAs and Chi Square

Post

Marriage Eq

# fit anova
fit_marriage_eq_prepost <- data_processed_after_exclusions %>%
  select(id, agree_with_marriage_equality_prepost, condition_type_of_pt, condition_level) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  ezANOVA(data     = .,
          dv       = agree_with_marriage_equality_prepost,
          between  = .(condition_type_of_pt, condition_level),
          wid      = id,
          type     = 3,
          detailed = TRUE)

# automatically format results
anova_out(fit_marriage_eq_prepost, print = FALSE)$`--- FORMATTED RESULTS ------------------------------------` %>%
  # print
  kable() %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"), full_width = FALSE)
Effect Text
(Intercept) F(1, 157) = 2695.71, p < .001, np2 = .94
condition_type_of_pt F(1, 157) = 0.85, p = .357, np2 = .01
condition_level F(2, 157) = 0.79, p = .456, np2 = .01
condition_type_of_pt:condition_level F(2, 157) = 0.68, p = .506, np2 = .01
